<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-101-290  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 101 290.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Dec 4 1989 v3 n49 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army plans to restructure ADP systems' architecture. (theSustaining Base Information Services system will replace the ArmyStandard Information Management System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Army will replace its Army Standard Information ManagementSystem (ASIMS) with the Sustaining Base Information Services(SBIS) system in what is expected to be a highly competitiveprocurement.andP;  SBIS is expected to cost $500 million; among thesystems integrators expected to compete for the contract areElectronic Data Systems, which was awarded the 10-year ASIMScontract in 1982, Computer Sciences Corp, Boeing Computer ServicesCo, Planning Research Corp, TRW Inc and Perot Systems Inc. TheArmy wants to replace its current batch processing-based systemusing IBM plug-compatible mainframes with a distributed, shareddata systems using an open architecture.andP;  Problems with ASIMS werenoted in a recent Army study, primarily in the area of efficiencyand cost-savings.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Electronic Data Systems Corp. (contracts).andO;Topic:     Computer ServicesComputer Systems IntegratorsGovernment ContractsGovernment AgencyEquipment AcquisitionOpen SystemsHardware SelectionUnited States. Army.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>